body: {"body": "Washington (CNN)Some Republicans seeking the White House blasted University of Missouri administrators for resigning in the wake of continued protests
byline: while Democrats said they were standing with students and others looking to address what they say is structural racism.\n\"I think it's just disgusting. I think the two people who resigned are weak
description: ineffective people
title: \" Donald Trump said on Fox News Thursday morning. \"When they resigned
url: they set something in motion that's going to be a disaster for the next long period of time.\"\nTrump also called the protestors' demands for change \"crazy.\"\n\"Many of those things are like crazy
topics: \" he said.\nMissouri's president and chancellor both resigned Tuesday
people: not long after the university's football players joined in the protests. The protests are over decades of complaints
org: but took shape after the student government president took to Facebook in September to complain about bigotry and racial slurs. \nRepublican Ben Carson
election_confidence: the only black candidate in the 2016 race
authors: said the resignations are a sign of the \"politically correct police\" going too far.\n\"It's OK to disagree with people
date_written: but it's not OK to destroy them
orgs: \" Carson said Thursday on Fox News. \"People are so frightened of the politically correct police that they are willing to do things that are irrational in order to appease them. I believe it's going to be necessary for those people who truly believe in our system
date_access: who believe in our principles and values that made America great
column15: to be willing to stand up.\"\nBut Democratic presidential candidates took sides with the students protesting racism on campus at the University of Missouri.\n\"I'm listening to the #BlackOnCampus conversation. It's time to address structural racism on college campuses
column16: \" Sanders tweeted. \nHillary Clinton retweeted her staffer Marlon Marshall
column19: let alone an institution of learning. Standing w/ the students at Mizzou in my home state calling for change.\"\nMarshall is a former Obama aide who helped oversee health care enrollment efforts.\nKentucky Sen. Rand Paul
column20: who is also seeking the GOP presidential nomination
column21: said Tuesday \"there's a certain amount of anger out there\" in response to a question about the clash between protesters and members of the media.\n\"I think freedom of speech is very
column22: very important. Does freedom of speech mean there will be boorish people who say things you don't want to associate with? Yes
column23: \" he said. \"But really in a free society
column24: there's got to be a place for people to make their argument.\" \nCNN's Eugene Scott and Jeremy Diamond contributed to this report."
column27: "title": "2016ers react to University of Missouri protests"

body: {"body": "President Barack Obama took his campaign to win passage of a proposed Pacific trade pact to more than 600
byline: 000 eBay Inc. users on Thursday.\nWriting to small business owners and retailers who use the online e-commerce platform
description: Mr. Obama said the proposed Trans-Pacific Partnership agreement would help small business owners broadly and Internet vendors in particular.\nThe agreement \u201clevels the playing field for you and your employees
title: bringing down trade barriers like high taxes and red tape
url: while preserving free and open digital data flows between you and your customers in the Asia-Pacific
topics: \u201d Mr. Obama wrote in a message that was sent by email to hundreds of thousands of eBay sellers and posted on a company website.\nThe outreach effort represents a new front in Mr. Obama\u2019s effort to sell the agreement to policymakers and the public \u00e2\u0080\u0094 enlisting small business owners in the effort to ratify one of Mr. Obama\u2019s final priorities. Major business lobbying groups like the U.S. Chamber of Commerce and the Business Roundtable have backed the trade agreement.\nThe 12-nation free trade pact was completed earlier this year and will now need to be ratified by Congress. Many Democrats and progressives oppose free trade agreements broadly
people: saying they cost American jobs and lower environmental and labor standards. Democratic presidential candidates Hillary Clinton and Bernie Sanders both oppose the agreement.\nRepublicans in Congress have been more supportive of the agreement \u00e2\u0080\u0094 though some specific provisions and sections of the TPP have rankled top Republicans.\nIn making his case to business owners
org: the president pointed to sections in the trade agreement that would govern data sharing and ensure that the internet remains open.\nHe also noted the agreement included a chapter on small businesses \u00e2\u0080\u0094 and would help reduce regulation and trade barriers for smaller companies trying to do global business.\nThose benefits include \u201celiminating 18

{"body": "The lieutenant governor’s office filed papers Thursday aimed at keeping two employees on loan from the California Senate but who have been notified they must return to the Senate for reassignment.
The Times has reported that a political rift had opened when Senate President Pro Tem Kevin De Leon (D-Los Angeles) took action to slash Democratic Lt. Gov. 
Gavin Newsom
’s staff just weeks after Newsom introduced a 2016 ballot initiative that includes one of De Leon’s pet policy proposals.
Newsom’s office manager and chief consultant for economic development were told to return to the Senate for reassignment Monday. They represent two of the six people working for the lieutenant governor.
Rhys Williams
byline: the lieutenant governor\u2019s chief of staff
description: said he filed papers with state personnel officials on Thursday to convert the two workers to full time employees of the lieutenant governor. Williams said the two workers will resign their Senate positions Friday to pave the way for the change.\n\u201cThey have expressed a desire to continue to work for the lieutenant governor
title: \u201d Williams said. \u201cThe decision has been made by them.\u201d\nNewsom is running for governor in 2018 and his candidacy may benefit from his leadership on the gun-control initiative. De Leon has formed a committee to campaign for lieutenant governor in 2018 and might also have received a boost if viewed as a leader on gun control.\nDe Leon had introduced a bill last year to require background checks for those who buy ammunition
url: and the same language was included in Newsom\u2019s initiative.\n\u201cThe record is relevant but a distraction from a key point and that is
topics: no one person should assume a monopoly of ownership on taking actions that make our communities safer

body: {"body": "Peggy Drexler is the author of \"Our Fathers
byline: Ourselves: Daughters
description: Fathers and the Changing American Family\" and \"Raising Boys Without Men.\" She is an assistant professor of psychology at Weill Cornell Medical College of Cornell University and a former gender scholar at Stanford University. Join her on Facebook and follow her on Twitter @drpeggydrexler. The opinions expressed in this commentary are solely those of the author. \n (CNN)This week
title: the election season took a turn for the predictable as Hillary Clinton's hair became the topic of conversation in a Donald Trump media appearance. \nTrump was chatting with Mark Levin
url: a conservative talk radio host who wanted to know what Trump suspected voters liked most about Clinton. Trump's response was characteristically provocative
topics: if entirely off-point: \"Well
org: \" Trump replied. \"Did you notice that today?\"\nThat wasn't all. He then went on to call Clinton's hair \"shocking
election_confidence: \" \"massive\" and agreeing with Levin's suggestion that the pile of hair atop his opponent's head \"must be\" a wig. \nPolitics as usual
authors: right? \nWhat a woman looks like -- her weight
orgs: how much makeup she does or doesn't wear --has remained stubbornly front and center in the world of working women
column15: public office. Despite being one of history's most successful female political figures
column16: Clinton has been judged for decades on how she looks: for those pantsuits
column17: for her choice of hair accessories
column20: many have argued that such comments are directed at Clinton
column22: simply because they're women; that no male candidate would be subjected to such constant analysis of hair
column26: in the wake of Trump's comments last night
column27: it would be easy to say that things haven't really changed; that even when talking about one of the world's most powerful women
column28: matters still come down to how good we think she looks.  \nExcept it's not entirely true that women are on the receiving end of all the focus on appearance.\nHillary Clinton
column30: made fun of Trump's hair in a bit on Jimmy Fallon (\"just one strand that he twirls over his head like a soft serve at Dairy Queen\")  And let's not forget all the girl talk about Mitt Romney's good looks or judgment of his expensive haircut as a signal of \"wealthy privilege.\" Meanwhile
column31: President Barack Obama's personal style continues to garner praise -- that is
column32: when he's not taking heat over his \"mom jeans.\" \nDonald Trump
column34: has no filter. He says what he thinks
column35: seemingly as soon as he thinks it
column36: and it's not always appetizing. That's why people love him
column37: and also why people don't. It's certainly why he's still generating headline news.  \nAnd yet
column38: in his conversation with the Levin -- which
column39: given that Levin is a well-known conservative
column40: had an agenda from the get-go -- Trump doesn't actually say anything negative or positive about Clinton's hair. He brings it up out of context
column41: sure. But he never actually says it doesn't look good. \nBut so what if he did? The truth is that appearance is part of life
column42: and a pretty big one. \nIn politics
column43: it may not be something to celebrate
column44: necessarily -- certainly not a legitimate reason to elect or not elect someone to office -- but it needn't be something to entirely ignore
column45: either. That's just not how the rest of the world works; why should politics be any different? \nMore importantly
column46: the way to end sexism isn't to stop acknowledging a woman's appearance altogether. That's not evolution; that's just forced silence
column47: which is quite possibly as damning
column49: as making appearance the only thing that matters. \nIn fact
column50: let's consider that the greatest amount of attention put on Clinton's new hairstyle wasn't Trump's doing; it was the doing of everyone else who took his comments and ran with them
column51: turning a blowhard's observation into something resembling an attack. \nClinton may very well be wearing a wig. It seems unlikely
column52: but who cares? Many women do. So do many men.\nDoes Trump? Well
column53: the world continues to marvel at his odd locks. Perhaps enduring many years of public taunting about them has encouraged him to do the same to others or at least sent him the message that the topic isn't off-limits. That
column55: is how bullies become bullies -- they've been subject to the teasing themselves.\nLet's make sure that from now on
column56: if anyone's going to do the bullying
column57: it's Trump. Not the rest of us. \nJoin us on Facebook.com/CNNOpinion.Read CNNOpinion's Flipboard magazine. \n"
column60: "title": "Wrong for Donald Trump to note Hillary Clinton's hair?"

body: {"body": "With the Democratic presidential nomination contest all but officially a two-person race
byline: Hillary Rodham Clinton appears vastly better positioned than Senator Bernie Sanders of Vermont to persuade party primary voters that she would be more effective at passing her agenda and dealing with international crises
description: according to a New York Times/CBS News survey released Thursday.\n\nMrs. Clinton even undercuts Mr. Sanders on his core political message
title: with 62 percent of Democratic primary voters saying she could bring about real change in Washington
url: compared with 51 percent for Mr. Sanders.\n\nThe promise of change
topics: always a popular lure in politics
people: is at the heart of a striking paradox in the Democratic race. Democratic primary voters say that the ability to deliver needed change is the most important quality they seek in a candidate
org: and Mr. Sanders\u2019s popularity is highest with voters who want change. Yet 60 percent of Democrats also want their nominee to continue President Obama\u2019s policies
election_confidence:
and these voters support Mrs. Clinton over Mr. Sanders by about a 2-to-1 margin.

This advantage for Mrs. Clinton may reflect all-around skepticism that Mr. Sanders’s leftist candidacy can prevail: Her party’s primary voters expect Mrs. Clinton to be their eventual nominee by more than a 4-to-1 margin over Mr. Sanders.

His chief indictment against Mrs. Clinton
authors: that she is an establishment politician who is captive to big-money special interests and inconsistent on liberal priorities
date_written: simply has not persuaded many Democrats to abandon her. While 84 percent of them see Mrs. Clinton as under the sway of special interests
orgs: she is still the heavy favorite among Democratic primary voters seeking a candidate who is a strong leader with the right experience to be president.\n\nAnd while Mr. Sanders is running as an unwavering liberal
article_id: three-quarters of Democratic primary voters prefer a nominee who would compromise with Republicans in Congress to get things done.\n\nAfter a month of sharpened attacks by Mr. Sanders against her
date_access: Mrs. Clinton has support from 52 percent of Democratic primary voters
column15: while Mr. Sanders has backing from 33 percent
column16: the poll found. The numbers are virtually unchanged from an early October CBS News poll
column17: in which she led Mr. Sanders
column18: 56 percent to 32 percent.\n\nThe nationwide telephone poll was conducted Nov. 6 to 10 on cellphones and landlines with 1
column21: and has a margin of sampling error of plus or minus six percentage points for Democratic primary voters.\n\nMrs. Clinton inspires more confidence among party members on a range of issues than the lesser known Mr. Sanders
column22: who is only now starting to run biographical advertisements on television. On a signature Sanders issue
column23: regulating large banks and financial institutions
column24: Mrs. Clinton inspired confidence in 70 percent of primary voters
column25: compared with 65 percent for Mr. Sanders. On gun laws
column26: 76 percent of Democratic primary voters think she would make the right decisions compared with 57 percent for Mr. Sanders
column27: whose votes against some gun-control measures have been highlighted by Mrs. Clinton.\n\nOn foreign conflicts
column29: Democrats overwhelmingly expressed more faith in the decision-making of Mrs. Clinton
column32: a longtime antiwar figure.\n\n\u201cShe knows all the players
column38: said in an interview after the poll was completed. She added
column40: \u201cShe has her husband behind her for advice.\u201d Three-quarters of Democrats view Bill Clinton favorably.\n\nBut support for Mrs. Clinton lags in some groups of Democratic primary voters
column41: particularly men and younger voters. Among the misgivings is one that has surfaced before in her political career: Fifty-two percent of Democratic primary voters think that Mrs. Clinton says what she actually believes
column42: compared with 62 percent who think Mr. Sanders is genuine in his remarks.\n\n\u201cIt\u2019s not so much I don\u2019t trust her
column43: but she seems to me to say what she thinks people want to hear
column46: a self-employed Democrat from East Haven
column48: who is leaning toward Mr. Sanders. \u201cShe has recently said something about legalizing marijuana
column49: which is a brand new position for her. I don\u2019t think she means anything she says.\u201d\n\nFor Mr. Sanders
column50: who is attracting bigger crowds than Mrs. Clinton and is running notably close to her in fund-raising
column51: the overarching challenge is to transform an insurgent primary campaign aimed at two must-win states
column53: into a formidable movement with broad national appeal. He will face his greatest test yet on Saturday night at the second Democratic debate
column54: which will be televised nationally from Des Moines. Nearly half of Democratic primary voters say they are very likely to watch the debate
column55: and an additional three in 10 said they were somewhat likely.\n\nMrs. Clinton will take the stage after a run of positive developments since their Oct. 13 debate
column56: including strong reviews of her performance there; Vice President Joseph R. Biden Jr.\u2019s decision not to enter the race; and a steely
column57: well-received face-off with congressional Republicans investigating the 2012 attack on the United States diplomatic compound in Benghazi
column58: Libya.\n\nMr. Sanders has been trying to undercut her political momentum by drawing more contrasts on policy
column59: noting that he has been more liberal for far longer than her on issues like free trade
column60: the death penalty and a single-payer health care system. Yet his attacks have not been memorably potent.\n\nA third Democratic candidate
column61: former Gov. Martin O\u2019Malley of Maryland
column62: will also take part in Saturday\u2019s debate
column63: but he is trailing far behind his rivals. He received 5 percent support in the Times/CBS News poll.\n\nMr. Sanders and Mr. O\u2019Malley have room to grow if they can find a way: Half of Democratic primary voters say it is still too early to say for sure whom they will support. And while Mr. Sanders is running closest behind Mrs. Clinton
column64: four in 10 voters still do not have an opinion of him \u2014 and many hold views that suggest they would be open to his platform.\n\nWhile some Sanders allies worry that his decades-long identification as a democratic socialist will hurt him
column65: 56 percent of Democratic primary voters say they hold a positive view of socialism. About nine in 10 think that the gap between rich and poor is an urgent problem
column66: and most would support raising taxes on the wealthy to deal with it \u2014 one of Mr. Sanders\u2019s major positions \u2014 and 78 percent oppose unlimited campaign contributions to fund-raising committees known as \u201csuper PACs
column67: \u201d as does Mr. Sanders. (Mrs. Clinton is supported by a such a fund-raising arm.)\n\nSue Moon
column68: a Seattle Democrat and a retired teacher
column69: said she did not like Mrs. Clinton\u2019s ties to wealthy donors and Wall Street executives
column70: some of whom Ms. Moon blames for the 2008 financial crisis.\n\n\u201cI am much more in favor of the wing of the party that thinks a lot of these people should have gone to jail
column72: a Sanders supporter.\n\nWhile the Republican presidential race is far more unsettled
column74: Democrats think that Donald J. Trump
column75: whose tough talk and outsize personality have energized many disaffected conservatives
column76: would be the toughest to beat in a general election. Thirty-one percent of Democrats said Mr. Trump would be the most formidable opponent next November
column77: while 15 percent named the retired neurosurgeon Ben Carson and 13 percent each picked former Gov. Jeb Bush of Florida and Senator Marco Rubio of Florida. Gov. John Kasich of Ohio and Senator Ted Cruz of Texas lagged far behind.\n\nLuke Cottrill
column78: a junior high school teacher and a Democrat in San Francisco
column79: said that Mr. Trump would be the most dangerous foe in a general election because he is not only a political outsider but also speaks pointedly in ways that resonate deeply with some people
column80: while offending others. Mr. Trump is also famous in a nation that worships celebrity
column81: Mr. Cottrill said.\n\n\u201cDonald Trump is a TV star
column82: and Ronald Reagan was a movie star \u2014 people know who he is
column85: and sometimes we Americans are impressed by demagogues and forget about their power over people.\u201d"
column88: 62 percent said Mrs. Clinton could bring about real change in Washington
column89: compared with 51 percent for Mr. Sanders."

column17: \" he said in a statement late Thursday
column18: and has asked the Pentagon's inspector general to investigate the matter.\n\"Today I made the decision to remove my Senior Military Assistant Lieutenant General Ron Lewis from his position after learning about allegations of misconduct
column20: without divulging the details of the allegations.\nStory Continued Below\n\"I have confidence in the Inspector General's ability to determine the facts. The Department of the Army will then take action as appropriate

THE CLOCK: 361 days until Election Day 2016 …

THE NARROWCAST DEBATE: POLITICO’s Gabriel Debenedetti reports: Iowa
column21: Iowa. That\u2019s the not-particularly-subtle message pervading Democratic camps as the party\u2019s three remaining presidential candidates prep for their second debate Saturday night in Des Moines
column22: a recognition that the first-caucusing state will likely play an even more outsized role than usual in 2016. \nWhile the direction of the questions may be squarely in the hands of debate host CBS News and moderator John Dickerson
column23: each of the candidates has already started sharpening the message (and spin) that they think will specifically take them furthest with the state\u2019s influential voters. \u201cThe Nevada debate was more of a national debate
column26: echoing the beliefs of other top Democrats. \u201cI do expect [this one] to be a debate that has more focus on Iowa.\"\nFor Sanders
column27: that means heading north to his Burlington headquarters for two days starting Wednesday night to sit down with aides
column28: and to scour briefing papers that include a deep-dive rundown on Iowa issues outlined by his staff on the ground there. He\u2019s agreed to participate in mock debate run-throughs \u2014 after being resistant to such standard pre-debate fare last time \u2014 and his staff expects that he'll prepare specific policy contrasts to unleash against front-runner HILLARY CLINTON before he flies out to Des Moines on Friday. http://politi.co/1METIPq\nTGIT
column29: and welcome to your 2016 Blast. Henry C. Jackson (@henrycjjackson) is here to guide you through today\u2019s campaign news. Send your tips
column31: and hottest hot takes to: hjackson@politico.com. \nTRAIL MIX: Here\u2019s what\u2019s popping on the campaign trail\nIn today\u2019s campaign news

column37: with agents exploring whether multiple statements violate a federal false statements statute
column38: according to intelligence sources familiar with the ongoing case \u2026 This phase represents an expansion of the FBI probe
column39: which is also exploring potential violations of an Espionage Act provision relating to \"gross negligence\" in the handling of national defense information.\u201d http://fxn.ws/1MDm0dc\nFASTER

body: {"body": " (AP) \u00e2\u0080\u0094 Republican presidential rivals Sens. Marco Rubio and Ted Cruz are backpedaling furiously as they try to outmaneuver each other on immigration.\nRubio co-wrote a massive 2013 immigration bill that passed the Senate. He disavows it now
byline: but Cruz won't stop talking about it.\nCruz opposed the bill
description: but he offered amendments to massively increase legal immigration. Now he says that's not a good idea after all
title: but Rubio won't let him off the hook.\nBoth senators are maneuvering to appeal to conservative GOP presidential primary voters in a campaign shadowed by Donald Trump
url: who wants to deport all 11.5 million immigrants in this country illegally. Trump's hard-line stance has pushed the entire GOP field to the right and may create problems for the eventual GOP nominee facing a more diverse general election electorate. Former Florida Gov. Jeb Bush pointed to that possibility in Tuesday night's GOP debate when he said that Hillary Rodham Clinton's Democratic campaign would be doing high-fives at such talk.\nOn Thursday Cruz did a complete about-face on one of his long-held immigration stances
topics: telling conservative talk host Laura Ingraham when asked whether he would increase the numbers of legal immigrants to the U.S.: \"I don't believe that's a good idea.\"\nBut during the Senate immigration debate two years ago the Texas senator was an outspoken advocate for increasing legal immigration
people: particularly for highly skilled immigrants. He called legal immigration \"a pillar of our nation's heritage and strength\" and introduced amendments to double the cap on legal immigration and increase the number of high-skilled immigrant visas by 500 percent.\nCruz also proposed an amendment to eliminate the path to citizenship in the Senate bill
org: allowing immigrants in the country illegally to end up with legal status short of citizenship instead.\nRubio highlighted those stances in a campaign appearance in South Carolina on Thursday
election_confidence: saying: \"Ted is a supporter of legalizing people that are in this country illegally. ... If you look at it
authors: I don't think our positions are dramatically different.\"\nBrian Phillips
article_id: arguing in a series of tweets that Cruz was not seeking to support legal status for immigrants in the country illegally
date_access: only to oppose citizenship. \"For the 1000th time
column15: his amdt had nothing to do with legalization. He intentionally focused on citizenship only ... to illustrate that Dems weren't serious about passing real reform.\"\nFor his part
column16: Cruz sought to use his appearance on Ingraham's show to highlight Rubio's role authoring the Senate immigration bill with its divisive path to citizenship for many of the immigrants in this country illegally. The legislation passed the Senate on a bipartisan vote in 2013 but ended up dying in the House
column17: and President Barack Obama ultimately addressed the issue through executive actions now tied up in court.\nWhen asked about Rubio
column19: \"You know where someone is based on their actions
column21: you shall know them by their fruits
column22: \"\nSpeaking of Rubio and the other authors of the Senate bill
column24: \"They fought tooth and nail to try to jam this amnesty down the American people's throat over and over and over again.\"\nRubio now says that a single
column25: comprehensive immigration bill is not the way to go and he would not address the status of the people in this country illegally before securing the border and remaking the legal immigration system. Ultimately he would still allow people here illegally to qualify for citizenship

body: {"body": "Washington  (CNN)Three more Republican presidential candidates added their names to the New Hampshire primary ballot on Thursday -- while making sure to heap praise on the first-in-the-nation primary state. \nSouth Carolina Sen. Lindsey Graham was the first GOPer of the day to file for the ballot in the state's capital of Concord
byline: followed by Texas Sen. Ted Cruz and former Pennsylvania Sen. Rick Santorum.\n\"From a personal point of view this is a bit emotional for me. I wish my parents were here
description: I think they are in spirit
title: \" Graham said while tearing up a bit.\n\"When you put benchmarks on your life
url: this is an incredible day for me
topics: \" Graham added.\nGraham also voiced his concern over using national polls to determine debate lineups. Graham failed to qualify for Tuesday's debate because of his low support in national polls. \n\"I've never been more worried about the early primary states than I am today
people: \" Graham said. \"The nationalization of this election by using national polls to determine who's qualified to speak
org:
undercuts the process that stood the test of time."
Cruz also defended New Hampshire's status as the nation's first primary when he filed in the Granite State Thursday.
